<br>
I remember for some of my first HoT raids in ToV (I was around 56 at the time I think), I'd be twisting ae resists, manasong, and occlusion (mob only spell) or baby slow or the baby stacking haste song (still around 15% I think) for my group, which generally had a couple healers and some various melee in it, often rangers.  Well, the healers in the group would start yelling at the rangers for filling all their buff slots, making it impossible for celestial healing to stick.  The rangers would then start to grumble about bard songs filling up their heal spot.  And I'd be sitting there; I'm not really singing many superfluous songs in these sorts of situations with only one or 2 bards at the raid.  Was call of earth REALLY that much more important than resists, mana song, or stacking haste?  So we all grouched at each other a bit, but sorted things out eventually and now those rangers and I love grouping on raids and otherwise.<br>
<br>
Same thing happened more recently with a PO chanter on a Tunare raid.  He started complaining about the uselessness of bard songs, ae manasong in particular.  I refrained from telling him that KEI (c3) was my favorite junk buff, since it did absolutely nothing for me and it lasted for ages.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Anyway, here are a few of the rules I've learned on buffs:<br>
<br>
1.  Rangers hate the paladin hp buff, known in various forms as Divine Strength, Brells, or Divine Vigor.  It overwrites many of their attack buffs, and since they are professional martyrs anyway, they don't mind doing without the extra couple hundred hp.<br>
<br>
2.  Druids hate Aegolism, since it overwrites their lvl 60 mana regen/hp/ac buff, Protection of the Glades.  Until the quest for potc was put in a few weeks ago, potg was also a group only spell (which didn't overwrite aegolism but), making it a very mana intensive &quot;self&quot; buff for a druid to recast.<br>
<br>
3.  Clerics who have Blessed Armor of the Risen (lvl 58 spell) hate the shaman focus spell, since it overwrites baotr, which is an excellent self-only hp/ac/mana regen buff for the cleric.<br>
<br>
4.  Everyone waits to ask for clarity/c2/c3 and haste until the pull.  The more mobs incoming, the more people who ask.<br>
<br>
5.  Everyone asks the shaman for buffs *as soon as* the poor dear is rezzed from his/her last slow.<br>
<br>
6.  When buffing for a mob that requires &quot;junk&quot; buffs, half the raid screams if bard manasong is running during the buff time, since it screws up their buff order and they like to ignore their instant clicky buff items till the fight.  The other half of the raid screams about manasong being turned off as soon as the harrassed bard listens to the first half.<br>
<br>
7.  Next to a chanter who has given out one too many clarities for the night, wizards are the grumpiest buffers.  They have already done their job getting you there, and want to relax during the course of the raid before they have to take you back home.  Most are rather dismayed about the existence of the Spellshield buff.<br>
<br>
I know more than one wizard who wants the mgb ability: not to make casting spellshield less painful, but rather to be able to cast group xloc bind and send the whole raid home en masse.  Frightening class.<br>
<br>
8.  Most warriors hate changing form, unless it involves shrinking or growing.  A few endure the imp form for the taunt aggro it gives, but not many.<br>
<br>
9.  Most rogues and bards LOVE changing form.  Many of them cycle illusions throughout the raid.  This endears them to the buffers.<br>
<br>
10.  All rangers and gnomes require rebuffing every 5 minutes due to their untimely deaths.  This endears them to the buffers.<br>
<br>
11.  Few people (besides those who die a lot, main tanks and otherwise) realize that rezzing takes a large amount of a cleric's mana; or that the cleric epic still has like, a 10 second casting time on it.<br>
<br>
Doubt that narrows it down or helps ya any, but was fun to write up.  /hides<br>
<br>
